{{italic title}}
{{canon law}}
'''''Vacatio legis''''' ({{lang-la|absence of law}}) is a technical term in both [[canon law (Catholic Church)|Catholic canon law]]<ref>[http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P3.HTM 1983 Code of Canon Law, Canon 8]</ref> and [[law|civil law]] which refers to the period between the [[promulgation]] of a [[law]] and the time the [[law]] takes legal effect.<ref>The Vatican Collection'' "Vatican Council II: Volume 1: The Conciliar and Post Conciliar Documents"'' (New Revised Edition, General Editor: Austin Flanery, [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]]), page 43, footnote "c"</ref><ref name=Manual70/>

==Canon law==
{{main|Promulgation (canon law)}}
{{further|Canon law (Catholic Church)|Jurisprudence of canon law}}
In the [[Canon law (Catholic Church)|canon law]] of the [[1983 Code of Canon Law|Latin Church]], the ''vacatio legis'' is three months for universal laws,<ref>[http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P3.HTM Canon 8 §1]</ref> and one month for particular laws,<ref>[http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P3.HTM Canon 8 §2]</ref> unless the law itself establishes a longer or shorter period of time.<ref>[http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P3.HTM Canon 8 §1]</ref><ref>[http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P3.HTM Canon 8 §2]</ref> Months are reckoned according to the calendar from the date of publication.<ref name=Manual70>Fernando della Rocca, "Manual of Canon Law", pg. 70 (§37)</ref> The law can stipulate a longer or shorter time of ''vacatio'' than that which is stipulated generally.<ref name=Manual70/>

[[Stanislaus Woywod]] says of ''vacatio legis'':
{{quote|The period of time allowed before a new law after its official [[promulgation (canon law)|promulgation]] goes into force is known in the terminology of [[canon law (Catholic Church)|Canon Law]] as the vacatio legis. [[canon lawyer|Canonists]] have generally held that for all laws promulgated by the [[Holy See]] two months time is granted before in places outside the [[Rome|City of Rome]] the obligation of observing the law begins. For very remote countries even a longer time has been conceded, in order to let the knowledge of the law become sufficiently disseminated to make its enforcement possible. In more recent times the Holy See has in important laws frequently specified the period of the vacatio legis, as for instance in the case of the [[decree (canon law)|decree]] Ne Tenure which was published about eight months before it was to be enforced. The general principle, however, valid in [[law|civil law]] as well as in Canon Law, is that it is the duty of subjects to keep themselves informed through the ordinary channels of information, as, for instance, official magazines and papers, what laws, amendments, decisions, etc., have been enacted by the authorities. It is not necessary, hence, that the bishop announce to his clergy the laws and regulations passed by the supreme authority of the Church, nor can it be said that this is his duty, though for uniformity of action on part of the clergy of a [[diocese]] it is advantageous that the bishop announce to his priests the important new laws with direction to make them known on one and the same day to the people throughout the diocese.<ref>Woywod, Rev. Stanislaus (1918).  [https://archive.org/stream/newcanonlaw00woywuoft/newcanonlaw00woywuoft_djvu.txt ''The New Canon Law''], pgs. v-vi. Internet Archive. Accessed 16 April 2016. {{PD-notice}}</ref>}}

==Civil law==
In [[civil law (legal system)|civil law]], ''vacatio legis'' "indicates a condition of non-validity of a norm, and because there is one that is already taken and yet to come into force (for the course prescribed time, or not yet taken for ratification or otherwise processing of the application procedure), and because you know or at least perceive the need for regulation of a subject to which, during the period, there are no rules.

